  <body>
    <div style="basic">
        <p begin="00:00:00" end="00:00:02.4" tts:direction="ltr">Hi, Data 2,100 students.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:02.4" end="00:00:05.9" tts:direction="ltr">In this video, we're going to talk about
<br/>data ecosystems.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:05.9" end="00:00:08.2" tts:direction="ltr">What does this mean? Let's talk about it.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:08.2" end="00:00:11.6" tts:direction="ltr">So when we're thinking about data
<br/>ecosystems,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:11.6" end="00:00:15.8" tts:direction="ltr">we are looking at a flow of information or
<br/>of data.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:15.8" end="00:00:19.8" tts:direction="ltr">This is a high level view, if you will,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:19.8" end="00:00:21.1" tts:direction="ltr">of a data ecosystem,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:21.1" end="00:00:24.3" tts:direction="ltr">and this isn't necessarily how every
<br/>organization looks.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:24.3" end="00:00:26.10" tts:direction="ltr">Rather, this is a nice blueprint or</p>
        <p begin="00:00:26.10" end="00:00:30.5" tts:direction="ltr">a template for a data ecosystem. Let's
<br/>step through this.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:30.5" end="00:00:33.9" tts:direction="ltr">We're going to start up here in the upper
<br/>left hand corner and think about</p>
        <p begin="00:00:33.9" end="00:00:37.7" tts:direction="ltr">this as this maybe being you as a user,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:37.7" end="00:00:41.2" tts:direction="ltr">potentially making some transactions.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:41.2" end="00:00:45.4" tts:direction="ltr">So this was a pop quiz and I told you that</p>
        <p begin="00:00:45.4" end="00:00:47.9" tts:direction="ltr">a company's blink are used to support</p>
        <p begin="00:00:47.9" end="00:00:50.7" tts:direction="ltr">day to day transactions and are updated
<br/>blank,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:50.7" end="00:00:54.1" tts:direction="ltr">what would you think about in the context
<br/>of a data ecosystem?</p>
        <p begin="00:00:54.1" end="00:00:56.5" tts:direction="ltr">If this is you as the end user making</p>
        <p begin="00:00:56.5" end="00:01:00.2" tts:direction="ltr">some purchase and this purchase is then
<br/>going</p>
        <p begin="00:01:00.2" end="00:01:07.8" tts:direction="ltr">into a company's blank that are used to
<br/>support day to day transactions,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:07.8" end="00:01:09.6" tts:direction="ltr">what would this blank be?</p>
        <p begin="00:01:09.6" end="00:01:11.8" tts:direction="ltr">That would be operational databases.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:11.8" end="00:01:15.6" tts:direction="ltr">A company's operational database is used
<br/>to support day to</p>
        <p begin="00:01:15.6" end="00:01:20.1" tts:direction="ltr">day transactions and are updated in real
<br/>time.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:20.1" end="00:01:25.3" tts:direction="ltr">If I'm going onto Amazon, making a
<br/>purchase,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:25.3" end="00:01:28.7" tts:direction="ltr">that is a transaction that's going to be
<br/>tracked in real time</p>
        <p begin="00:01:28.7" end="00:01:33.5" tts:direction="ltr">as update the inventory and get that order
<br/>shipped out.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:33.5" end="00:01:38.9" tts:direction="ltr">That is the second piece of our data
<br/>ecosystem is those operational databases.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:38.9" end="00:01:40.4" tts:direction="ltr">Me as an end user,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:40.4" end="00:01:41.7" tts:direction="ltr">I make a purchase.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:41.7" end="00:01:43.1" tts:direction="ltr">When I make that purchase,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:43.1" end="00:01:45.4" tts:direction="ltr">it goes down into that operational
<br/>database.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:45.4" end="00:01:47.1" tts:direction="ltr">Let's give an example here.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:47.1" end="00:01:51.1" tts:direction="ltr">Naturally, Say that I was really
<br/>interested</p>
        <p begin="00:01:51.1" end="00:01:55.10" tts:direction="ltr">in doing something like buying a tortilla
<br/>blanket.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:56.4" end="00:02:02.2" tts:direction="ltr">I have this tortilla blanket here and I
<br/>say that with this tortilla blanket,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:02.2" end="00:02:04.7" tts:direction="ltr">I'm going to purchase this tortilla
<br/>blanket.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:04.7" end="00:02:09.5" tts:direction="ltr">I have a screenshot over here of
<br/>purchasing this tortilla blanket.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:09.5" end="00:02:12.6" tts:direction="ltr">Now, once I purchase this blanket,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:12.6" end="00:02:18.6" tts:direction="ltr">that purchase is going to be tracked here
<br/>in my operational database.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:18.6" end="00:02:23.6" tts:direction="ltr">This is me making that purchase tracked in
<br/>that operational database.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:23.6" end="00:02:30.9" tts:direction="ltr">Okay. Perfect. Then now that transaction
<br/>is in my operational database,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:30.9" end="00:02:32.4" tts:direction="ltr">we're going on to question number two,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:32.4" end="00:02:35.3" tts:direction="ltr">which says a blink is a central repository
<br/>for</p>
        <p begin="00:02:35.3" end="00:02:37.6" tts:direction="ltr">all company data and may be</p>
        <p begin="00:02:37.6" end="00:02:40.2" tts:direction="ltr">considered as the official source of data
<br/>for the company.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:40.2" end="00:02:43.2" tts:direction="ltr">Its primary purpose is to support blink.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:43.2" end="00:02:49.1" tts:direction="ltr">What do we think about that? Central
<br/>repository for all company data. Hmm.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:49.1" end="00:02:51.7" tts:direction="ltr">So this is something that near and dear to
<br/>my heart.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:51.7" end="00:02:54.4" tts:direction="ltr">Yes, a data warehouse is near and dear to
<br/>my heart.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:54.4" end="00:02:56.6" tts:direction="ltr">But I teach a data warehousing class.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:56.6" end="00:02:58.5" tts:direction="ltr">That's the other class that I teach.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:58.5" end="00:03:01.1" tts:direction="ltr">It is the central repository for all data.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:01.1" end="00:03:02.6" tts:direction="ltr">We're talking about how do</p>
        <p begin="00:03:02.6" end="00:03:09.6" tts:direction="ltr">we design a data warehouse that supports
<br/>the company's mission.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:09.6" end="00:03:13.6" tts:direction="ltr">That's a really unique class to teach and
<br/>it's really fun.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:13.6" end="00:03:16.6" tts:direction="ltr">But it is all about how do we store</p>
        <p begin="00:03:16.6" end="00:03:20.4" tts:direction="ltr">the organization's central repository of
<br/>all of their data.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:20.4" end="00:03:24.4" tts:direction="ltr">Its primary purpose is to support data
<br/>analytics.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:24.4" end="00:03:31.9" tts:direction="ltr">Once once we have that transaction tracked
<br/>here in my operational database.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:31.9" end="00:03:34.10" tts:direction="ltr">I bought the tortilla blanket.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:34.10" end="00:03:39.9" tts:direction="ltr">That data then gets stored at some point
<br/>into the data warehouse.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:39.9" end="00:03:42.2" tts:direction="ltr">That may be that that data is being pulled
<br/>from</p>
        <p begin="00:03:42.2" end="00:03:46.3" tts:direction="ltr">that operational database to that data
<br/>warehouse every hour.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:46.3" end="00:03:48.9" tts:direction="ltr">It may be way more frequent than that.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:48.9" end="00:03:50.6" tts:direction="ltr">It may be everyday at five,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:50.6" end="00:03:54.5" tts:direction="ltr">it may be whatever the company's needs
<br/>are.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:54.5" end="00:03:57.2" tts:direction="ltr">It may be once a week on</p>
        <p begin="00:03:57.2" end="00:04:00.2" tts:direction="ltr">a Saturday when the servers aren't busy
<br/>doing other things.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:00.2" end="00:04:02.1" tts:direction="ltr">It just depends.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:02.1" end="00:04:03.8" tts:direction="ltr">But we're going to eventually pull</p>
        <p begin="00:04:03.8" end="00:04:05.9" tts:direction="ltr">that data from the operational database
<br/>into</p>
        <p begin="00:04:05.9" end="00:04:10.3" tts:direction="ltr">the data warehouse as a central repository
<br/>for our data, okay.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:10.3" end="00:04:14.1" tts:direction="ltr">So an operational database versus a data
<br/>warehouse.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:14.1" end="00:04:16.5" tts:direction="ltr">Let's talk about those different just
<br/>generally.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:16.5" end="00:04:18.7" tts:direction="ltr">When we think about a data warehouse,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:18.7" end="00:04:23.1" tts:direction="ltr">we are looking at data collected from a
<br/>lot of different sources.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:23.1" end="00:04:26.4" tts:direction="ltr">So a ton of different sources are going to
<br/>be pulling in</p>
        <p begin="00:04:26.4" end="00:04:29.7" tts:direction="ltr">data or we're going to be pulling data
<br/>into that data warehouse.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:29.7" end="00:04:32.6" tts:direction="ltr">Maybe it's a variety of different
<br/>operational databases,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:32.6" end="00:04:35.5" tts:direction="ltr">maybe it's a bunch of different reports
<br/>that are coming in.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:35.5" end="00:04:40" tts:direction="ltr">Maybe it's data coming from our customer
<br/>service management tool.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:40" end="00:04:42.1" tts:direction="ltr">It's a variety of different places.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:42.1" end="00:04:45.9" tts:direction="ltr">Streaming data, we're going to capture
<br/>data from in my data warehouse.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:45.9" end="00:04:49" tts:direction="ltr">Again, that's my central repository for
<br/>all data.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:49" end="00:04:53.7" tts:direction="ltr">You're talking a ton of data stored in
<br/>that data warehouse.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:53.7" end="00:04:56.3" tts:direction="ltr">Operational databases though, you're</p>
        <p begin="00:04:56.3" end="00:04:58.7" tts:direction="ltr">focusing more on just transaction
<br/>processing,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:58.7" end="00:05:00.7" tts:direction="ltr">there's transactions being made.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:00.7" end="00:05:03.2" tts:direction="ltr">This is data captured as is</p>
        <p begin="00:05:03.2" end="00:05:07" tts:direction="ltr">generally from a single source such as a
<br/>transactional system.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:08.5" end="00:05:12.5" tts:direction="ltr">This is really just looking at capturing
<br/>that data</p>
        <p begin="00:05:12.5" end="00:05:16.5" tts:direction="ltr">in those transactions where the data
<br/>warehouse is focusing more on,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:16.5" end="00:05:19.7" tts:direction="ltr">now that we're pulling all this data in
<br/>from all these different sources,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:19.7" end="00:05:22.1" tts:direction="ltr">we are going to now use it to run
<br/>analytics,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:22.1" end="00:05:23.3" tts:direction="ltr">to do reporting, to use big data.</p>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        <p begin="00:05:23.3" end="00:05:28.7" tts:direction="ltr">Okay. Not only does an operational
<br/>database and a data warehouse definitions,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:28.7" end="00:05:30.9" tts:direction="ltr">they're different, their purposes are
<br/>different.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:30.9" end="00:05:32.5" tts:direction="ltr">They also look a little bit different.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:32.5" end="00:05:34.7" tts:direction="ltr">Here's an entity relationship diagram.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:34.7" end="00:05:38.1" tts:direction="ltr">You're familiar with these with an
<br/>operational database.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:38.1" end="00:05:40.8" tts:direction="ltr">This is a highly normalized schema.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:40.8" end="00:05:44.2" tts:direction="ltr">That normalization is an entire process
<br/>that you</p>
        <p begin="00:05:44.2" end="00:05:47.5" tts:direction="ltr">go through in building a transactional
<br/>database.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:47.5" end="00:05:50.1" tts:direction="ltr">That's something that I expect you to know
<br/>in this class.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:50.1" end="00:05:53.4" tts:direction="ltr">I just want you to recognize that with
<br/>this operational database,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:53.4" end="00:05:56.10" tts:direction="ltr">we have here suppliers as related to
<br/>products,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:56.10" end="00:05:59.5" tts:direction="ltr">products as related to order details,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:59.5" end="00:06:01.4" tts:direction="ltr">products as related to categories,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:01.4" end="00:06:02.10" tts:direction="ltr">we have customers and orders related,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:02.10" end="00:06:06.1" tts:direction="ltr">employees um, orders related and shippers
<br/>are related.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:06.1" end="00:06:11.4" tts:direction="ltr">If I wanted to query from suppliers on
<br/>down to shippers,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:11.4" end="00:06:14.3" tts:direction="ltr">I would have to query a five table join.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:14.3" end="00:06:14.6" tts:direction="ltr">But conversely, if, for example,</p>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    <p begin="00:06:14.6" end="00:06:16.3" tts:direction="ltr">What does a data warehouse look like?</p>
        <p begin="00:06:16.3" end="00:06:18.4" tts:direction="ltr">A data warehouse looks a little bit
<br/>different.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:18.4" end="00:06:21" tts:direction="ltr">There is a central fact table,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:21" end="00:06:26.8" tts:direction="ltr">and then there's dimension tables to
<br/>describe that fact.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:26.8" end="00:06:32.1" tts:direction="ltr">A fact sales table holds my key
<br/>performance indicators like,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:32.1" end="00:06:34.8" tts:direction="ltr">Oh, hey, what was the quantity sold of a
<br/>product,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:34.8" end="00:06:37.2" tts:direction="ltr">the unit price, the sales amount, those
<br/>things.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:37.2" end="00:06:39.4" tts:direction="ltr">That's all held in my sales table.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:39.4" end="00:06:43.9" tts:direction="ltr">Then that fact table is then related to
<br/>DIM product,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:43.9" end="00:06:47.7" tts:direction="ltr">to DIM salesperson, to DMD, things like
<br/>that.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:47.7" end="00:06:51.6" tts:direction="ltr">If I wanted to query a table and say,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:51.6" end="00:06:54.8" tts:direction="ltr">Hey, I wanted to query from DIM product to
<br/>fact sales.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:54.8" end="00:06:57" tts:direction="ltr">We can see here that I'm only going to do,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:57" end="00:06:58.7" tts:direction="ltr">maybe at max here,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:58.7" end="00:07:00.10" tts:direction="ltr">write a three table join that way.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:00.10" end="00:07:05.6" tts:direction="ltr">So you'll notice that oftentimes a star
<br/>schema is going to</p>
        <p begin="00:07:05.6" end="00:07:10.8" tts:direction="ltr">reduce the number of joins that you're
<br/>going to be doing in your queries.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:10.8" end="00:07:15.1" tts:direction="ltr">This is going to help your queries run
<br/>significantly faster, right.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:15.1" end="00:07:17.7" tts:direction="ltr">There's other benefits to data warehouses.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:17.7" end="00:07:19.4" tts:direction="ltr">I could talk about this for a long time,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:19.4" end="00:07:22.3" tts:direction="ltr">so I'm trying to not spend too much time
<br/>here.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:22.3" end="00:07:24.1" tts:direction="ltr">I just want you to know that there is a
<br/>difference in</p>
        <p begin="00:07:24.1" end="00:07:26.2" tts:direction="ltr">the way that they are designed and</p>
        <p begin="00:07:26.2" end="00:07:30.2" tts:direction="ltr">there's a difference in their purpose and
<br/>transactional databases,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:30.2" end="00:07:32.4" tts:direction="ltr">data warehouses both have their place.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:32.4" end="00:07:35.9" tts:direction="ltr">They just have different purposes, okay?
<br/>All right.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:35.9" end="00:07:37.7" tts:direction="ltr">Back to my tortilla blanket.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:37.7" end="00:07:41.10" tts:direction="ltr">I know I had you on the edge of your seat
<br/>about this tortilla blanket.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:41.10" end="00:07:45.1" tts:direction="ltr">When I'm checking out this tortilla
<br/>blanket,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:45.1" end="00:07:47.9" tts:direction="ltr">I'm buying this tortilla blanket?</p>
        <p begin="00:07:47.9" end="00:07:49.9" tts:direction="ltr">I already bought it, and then it says,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:49.9" end="00:07:51.7" tts:direction="ltr">Hey, make sure to buy it with,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:51.7" end="00:07:54.1" tts:direction="ltr">and it gives me other options of things
<br/>like</p>
        <p begin="00:07:54.1" end="00:07:58.3" tts:direction="ltr">this giant breadstick looking pillow,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:58.3" end="00:08:01.1" tts:direction="ltr">and then maybe some other blanket.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:01.1" end="00:08:03" tts:direction="ltr">This buy it with,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:03" end="00:08:05.8" tts:direction="ltr">why does Amazon do that or</p>
        <p begin="00:08:05.8" end="00:08:09.9" tts:direction="ltr">products related to this or whatever? Why
<br/>does it do it?</p>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      <p begin="00:08:09.9" end="00:08:14.7" tts:direction="ltr">The reason that it does it is because
<br/>these are products that have been</p>
        <p begin="00:08:14.7" end="00:08:22.2" tts:direction="ltr">purchased by customers who also purchased
<br/>looked at this tortilla blanket.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:22.2" end="00:08:25.5" tts:direction="ltr">We call this a market basket analysis.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:25.5" end="00:08:28.6" tts:direction="ltr">What a market basket analysis does is it
<br/>says, Hey,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:28.6" end="00:08:31.4" tts:direction="ltr">if I know a customers purchased this
<br/>product,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:31.4" end="00:08:34.4" tts:direction="ltr">how much more likely are they to purchase
<br/>this other product?</p>
        <p begin="00:08:34.4" end="00:08:37.2" tts:direction="ltr">This is how a lot of grocery stores are
<br/>designed.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:37.2" end="00:08:39.7" tts:direction="ltr">You walk into a grocery store,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:39.7" end="00:08:44.2" tts:direction="ltr">and peanut butter and jelly are going to
<br/>be right next to each other.</p>
